   "source": [
    "# **ðŸ“Š Dataset Description - Google Play Store Apps Data**\n",
    "The dataset contains a comprehensive collection of app data from the Google Play Store, providing a snapshot of the app market landscape. It includes over 10,000 records with detailed information for each application. \n",
    "Key attributes tracked include:\n",
    "\n",
    "**App Identification:** App name and its primary Category.\n",
    "\n",
    "**User Engagement Metrics:** Rating (average user score), Reviews (total number of reviews), and Installs (number of user installations).\n",
    "\n",
    "**App Characteristics:** Size (app's download size), Type (Free or Paid), and Price.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Content & Classification:** Content Rating (e.g., Everyone, Teen, Mature), and Genres (a more specific classification than Category).\n",
    "\n",
    "**Version Information:** Last Updated, Current Ver, and Android Ver.\n",
    "\n",
    "This rich dataset enables in-depth analysis of app market trends, factors driving app popularity, user sentiment patterns, and monetization strategies across various categories.\n",
    "\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "0f5c2507-d3b2-4bfb-a6ce-f2f2df6f6c97",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# **ðŸ“– Project Overview**\n",
    "This project provides a complete end-to-end analysis of the Google Play Store dataset using Big Data Analytics with PySpark. The primary objective was to process and analyze this large dataset to extract meaningful insights about the mobile app ecosystem.\n",
    "\n",
    "The project followed a structured data analysis pipeline:\n",
    "\n",
    "**Data Cleaning and Preprocessing:** We first addressed significant data quality issues, including handling corrupted rows, cleaning inconsistent data formats (like symbols in numeric fields), and casting columns to their correct data types to prepare the data for reliable analysis.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA):** Key metrics were calculated to understand the dataset's composition. This included identifying the most dominant app categories, the distribution of free versus paid apps, and the overall spread of user ratings.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Data Visualization:** Using libraries like Matplotlib and Seaborn, we created a series of visualizationsâ€”including bar charts, histograms, pie charts, and heatmapsâ€”to visually represent trends and relationships within the data, making complex patterns easy to understand.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Targeted Analysis:** Finally, we performed a deeper analysis by filtering for a specific subset of \"Highly Successful Apps\" to uncover the common characteristics of top-performing applications on the Play Store. The results of this final analysis were then saved to a clean CSV file for reporting.\n",
    "\n"
   ]

    "\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "# 1. Import all necessary functions at the top\n",
    "from pyspark.sql.functions import col, regexp_replace, when, avg\n",
    "from pyspark.sql.types import IntegerType, FloatType\n",
    "\n",
    "# 2. Remove the single known corrupted row from the dataset first\n",
    "df_filtered = df.filter(df[\"App\"] != \"Life Made WI-Fi Touchscreen Photo Frame\")\n",
    "\n",
    "# 3. Clean and Cast the 'Rating' column\n",
    "df_cleaned = df_filtered.na.drop(subset=[\"Rating\"])\n",
    "# --- ADD THIS LINE HERE ---\n",
    "df_cleaned = df_cleaned.withColumn(\"Rating\", col(\"Rating\").cast(FloatType()))\n",
    "\n",
    "# 4. Clean the 'Installs' column\n",
    "df_cleaned = df_cleaned.withColumn(\"Installs\", regexp_replace(col(\"Installs\"), \"[+,]\", \"\"))\n",
    "df_cleaned = df_cleaned.withColumn(\"Installs\", col(\"Installs\").cast(IntegerType()))\n",
    "\n",
    "# 5. Clean the 'Price' column\n",
    "df_cleaned = df_cleaned.withColumn(\"Price\", regexp_replace(col(\"Price\"), \"\\\\$\", \"\"))\n",
    "df_cleaned = df_cleaned.withColumn(\"Price\", col(\"Price\").cast(FloatType()))\n",
    "\n",
    "# 6. Clean the 'Size' column (ROBUST FIX)\n",
    "# Use .endswith() instead of .contains() to be more specific.\n",
    "df_cleaned = df_cleaned.withColumn(\n",
    "    \"Size\",\n",
    "    when(col(\"Size\").endswith(\"M\"), regexp_replace(col(\"Size\"), \"M\", \"\").cast(FloatType()))\n",
    "    .when(col(\"Size\").endswith(\"k\"), regexp_replace(col(\"Size\"), \"k\", \"\").cast(FloatType()) / 1024)\n",
    "    .otherwise(None) # Set 'Varies with device' and any other non-matching values to null\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "# 7. Calculate the average size, ignoring all the nulls we just created\n",
    "average_size = df_cleaned.select(avg(\"Size\")).first()[0]\n",
    "\n",
    "# 8. Fill the null values in 'Size' (including 'Varies with device') with the calculated average\n",
    "df_cleaned = df_cleaned.na.fill({\"Size\": average_size})\n",
    "\n",
    "# 9. Convert 'Reviews' to Integer\n",
    "df_cleaned = df_cleaned.withColumn(\"Reviews\", col(\"Reviews\").cast(IntegerType()))\n",
    "\n",
    "# 10. FINAL CLEANING STEP: Ensure 'Type' column is valid\n",
    "# Keep only the rows where the 'Type' is either 'Free' or 'Paid'\n",
    "df_cleaned = df_cleaned.filter((col(\"Type\") == \"Free\") | (col(\"Type\") == \"Paid\"))\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "# Show the final cleaned schema and sample data in a perfect table\n",
    "print(\"--- Cleaned Dataset Schema ---\")\n",
    "df_cleaned.printSchema()\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"\\n--- Cleaned Sample Data ---\")\n",
    "df_cleaned.limit(5).toPandas()\n",
    "\n"
   ]
  },

   "cell_type": "code",

   "source": [
    "import os\n",
    "import shutil\n",
    "\n",
    "def save_spark_df_as_single_csv(spark_df, temp_folder, final_filepath):\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    Saves a Spark DataFrame to a single CSV file by writing to a temporary\n",
    "    folder, finding the part-file, and then moving/renaming it.\n",
    "    Includes a Pandas fallback, just like the reference notebook.\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    try:\n",
    "        # Use coalesce(1) to force the output into a single partition/file\n",
    "        spark_df.coalesce(1).write.option(\"header\", True).mode(\"overwrite\").csv(temp_folder)\n",
    "\n",
    "        # Find the part-xxxxx.csv file that Spark created\n",
    "        part_file = [f for f in os.listdir(temp_folder) if f.startswith(\"part-\") and f.endswith(\".csv\")][0]\n",
    "        part_filepath = os.path.join(temp_folder, part_file)\n",
    "\n",
    "        # Move and rename the part-file to the final desired path\n",
    "        shutil.move(part_filepath, final_filepath)\n",
    "\n",
    "        # Clean up the now-empty temporary folder\n",
    "        shutil.rmtree(temp_folder)\n",
    "\n",
    "        print(f\"âœ… Successfully saved DataFrame to: {final_filepath}\")\n",
    "\n",
    "    except Exception as e:\n",
    "        print(f\"âš ï¸ Spark write failed: {e}. Attempting Pandas fallback.\")\n",
    "        try:\n",
    "            # Fallback to using Pandas for saving, which is simpler\n",
    "            spark_df.toPandas().to_csv(final_filepath, index=False)\n",
    "            print(f\"âœ… Successfully saved DataFrame using Pandas fallback to: {final_filepath}\")\n",
    "        except Exception as pandas_e:\n",
    "            print(f\"âŒ Both Spark and Pandas saving methods failed: {pandas_e}\")\n"
   ]
  },

    "\n",
    "## **Conclusion**\n",
    "\n",
    "This project successfully performed a comprehensive, end-to-end analysis of the Google Play Store dataset using PySpark for large-scale data processing and Python's visualization libraries for creating insightful charts. Through a rigorous process of data cleaning, exploratory analysis, and targeted investigation, we have uncovered several key insights into the mobile app ecosystem.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Key Findings:**\n",
    "\n",
    "1.  **Data Quality is Paramount:** The initial dataset was fraught with inconsistencies, including corrupted rows, improper data types, and formatting errors. Our cleaning process was critical in transforming this raw data into a reliable asset, reinforcing the principle that no accurate analysis is possible without a clean foundation.\n",
    "\n",
    "2.  **The \"Freemium\" Economy Dominates:** Our analysis confirmed that the Google Play Store is overwhelmingly dominated by free applications, which constitute over 92% of the offerings. This indicates that monetization strategies primarily revolve around in-app advertising and in-app purchases rather than upfront costs.\n",
    "\n",
    "3.  **User Engagement Drives Visibility:** A strong positive correlation was found between the number of user `Installs` and the number of `Reviews`. This confirms the intuitive idea that as an app gains popularity, its user base becomes more vocal, creating a feedback loop that further enhances visibility and credibility.\n",
    "\n",
    "4.  **Category Saturation and Opportunity:** While the \"FAMILY\" and \"GAME\" categories have the highest number of apps, indicating a highly saturated market, our analysis of \"highly successful apps\" revealed that top-tier applications are also prevalent in categories like \"COMMUNICATION,\" \"PHOTOGRAPHY,\" and \"SOCIAL.\" This suggests that while competition is fierce, high-quality apps can succeed across a diverse range of categories.\n",
    "\n",
    "5.  **No Single Metric Guarantees Success:** The heatmap analysis showed that while installs and reviews are linked, other factors like `Rating`, `Price`, and `Size` do not show strong correlations with app popularity on their own. This implies that app success is a multifaceted outcome that depends on a combination of factors, including user experience, marketing, and the app's intrinsic value, rather than just one or two simple metrics.[3]\n",
    "\n",
    "Ultimately, this project not only provided a detailed snapshot of the Google Play Store market but also served as a practical demonstration of applying a big data analytics pipeline. The insights gathered can guide developers and marketers in making data-driven decisionsâ€”from choosing a competitive category to setting a pricing strategy and focusing on user engagement to climb the ranks.\n"
   ]
